<BlogPost
	title="Ferry Beach State Park: Maine's Quiet Beach Near Saco"
	description="Two miles from Saco Bay Hotel, Ferry Beach is one of Maine's most underrated state parks — a wide sandy beach, rare tupelo trees, and a lot fewer people than Old Orchard."
	date="April 2026"
	category="Nature Guide"
	slug="ferry-beach-state-park"
>
	<p>Ferry Beach State Park sits two miles from Saco Bay Hotel, tucked between Old Orchard Beach and Camp Ellis on the same continuous sandy shore. It's a 117-acre Maine State Park with a wide Atlantic beach, 1.7 miles of nature trails, and a genuine ecological peculiarity: a stand of tupelo trees growing at the very northern limit of their species' range — a botanical feature that draws naturalists from across the region.</p>

	<p>More practically: it's a beautiful beach that most of the crowds at Old Orchard never find.</p>

	<h2>The Beach</h2>

	<p>Ferry Beach is part of the same long barrier beach system as Old Orchard — the same white sand, the same gentle surf, the same Saco Bay views. The difference is the crowd. Where Old Orchard Beach is a social event, Ferry Beach is a state park with a parking lot and a fee booth. The visitors who make it here tend to be there for the nature, which means quiet, space, and a beach that doesn't feel like a boardwalk.</p>

	<p><strong>Swimming is permitted.</strong> Lifeguards are on duty from mid-June through mid-August. Beyond that window, you swim at your own judgment — conditions are typically calm.</p>

	<p><strong>No pets on the beach or boardwalk from April 1 through September 30.</strong> The ferry Beach nature trails within the park are open year-round to leashed dogs.</p>

	<h2>The Tupelo Trees</h2>

	<p>The park's most unusual feature is a stand of Tupelo trees (black gum trees) growing in the freshwater swamp behind the beach dunes. Tupelo is native to the American South and mid-Atlantic — its presence in Saco is a genuine botanical anomaly, at the extreme northern edge of where the species can survive.</p>

	<p>The <strong>Tupelo Trail</strong> is a 0.4-mile path on a raised boardwalk through the swamp, allowing visitors to walk through without getting wet. The boardwalk is largely <strong>barrier-free</strong> — accessible for strollers and wheelchairs. In autumn, the black gum trees turn brilliant crimson-red, producing some of the most striking fall foliage in any small Maine park.</p>

	<h2>The Trail Network</h2>

	<p>Total trail network: 1.7 miles, mostly barrier-free.</p>

	<ul>
		<li><strong>Tupelo Trail (0.4 mi):</strong> The raised boardwalk swamp walk. The must-do trail. Easy, accessible, and genuinely unusual.</li>
		<li><strong>White Oak Trail:</strong> Winds through a towering deciduous hardwood forest.</li>
		<li><strong>Red Oak Trail:</strong> A forested loop under a large oak canopy.</li>
	</ul>

	<p>The trail network is connected and can be combined for a 1–2 hour walk through multiple distinct ecosystems: ocean beach, coastal dunes, freshwater swamp, and deciduous hardwood forest — all within a 117-acre park.</p>

	<h2>Birdwatching</h2>

	<p>Ferry Beach is a noted birding location due to the variety of habitats packed into a small area. <strong>Warblers</strong> are a highlight during spring and fall migration. The park is listed as a birding hotspot on eBird (hotspot ID: L1590215).</p>

	<p>Other wildlife includes white-tailed deer, various amphibians in the swamp, and shorebirds along the beach. The birding is genuinely productive in May during peak warbler migration — a feature that draws serious birders from the Portland area.</p>

	<h2>Fees</h2>

	<p>Maine State Parks day-use fees (standard rates — verify at maine.gov/dacf/parks):</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Maine residents (age 12+):</strong> $3.00 per person per day</li>
		<li><strong>Non-residents (age 12+):</strong> $4.50 per person per day</li>
		<li><strong>Children ages 5–11:</strong> $1.00</li>
		<li><strong>Children under 5:</strong> Free</li>
		<li><strong>Maine residents age 65+:</strong> Free at all state parks</li>
		<li><strong>Annual Vehicle Pass:</strong> $105 | <strong>Individual Annual Pass:</strong> $55</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Hours and Facilities</h2>

	<p><strong>Open daily 9:00 AM to sunset</strong>, Memorial Day through September 30.</p>

	<p>Facilities include changing rooms and restrooms adjacent to the parking lot, a picnic area, a group picnic shelter, and the accessible barrier-free trail network. No food concessions on site — bring your own.</p>

	<h2>Best Times to Visit</h2>

	<p><strong>Summer (late June–August):</strong> Full lifeguard coverage, beach swimming, nature center programs. Best for families with young children who want a beach day without the OOB crowds.</p>

	<p><strong>Fall (September–October):</strong> The black gum trees turn crimson — among the most striking fall foliage of any small Maine park. Crowds drop dramatically after Labor Day. September is an excellent shoulder-season option: water still warm, park quiet, full foliage approaching.</p>

	<p><strong>Spring migration (May):</strong> Exceptional birdwatching as warblers pass through in numbers. The swamp is active, the oak forest is leafing out, and the park is nearly empty.</p>

	<h2>Getting There</h2>

	<p>95 Bay View Road, Saco, ME 04072. From Saco Bay Hotel, head south toward Old Orchard Beach, then follow Bay View Road toward the waterfront. The entrance is well-marked from Route 9. About a 5-minute drive.</p>

	<div class="tip-box">
		<strong>Ferry Beach vs. Old Orchard</strong>
		<p>If you're staying at Saco Bay Hotel and want a beach day that doesn't involve navigating OOB parking and crowds, Ferry Beach is the answer. Same sand, same bay — just two miles down the road, a state park fee booth, and dramatically fewer people. Bring lunch and do the Tupelo Trail after the beach.</p>
	</div>
